    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="concession">Although I suppose I am a &quot;constructivist&quot; in my theory of knowledge and
social theory,</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="22" relname="span"> I am not a relativist, methodological or otherwise. </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="23" relname="span"> I don&apos;t
know why these are always linked.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="24" relname="span"> BUT, why would relativism count against
academic freedom?</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="33" relname="span"> Wouldn&apos;t the most obvious political implication be a
concern with expanded, more effective academic freedom as against allegedly
free but in fact coercive institutions?</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="34" relname="span">

Of course, this raises a whole can of worms,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="31" relname="span"> but they have been discussed
with more precision elsewhere. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="25" relname="span"> See for instance the discsussions about
radical democracry in the post-marxism of Laclau, Mouffe, Zizek and the like
which simultaneously takes marxism to task for its (antidemocratic) critique
of &quot;bourgeous democracy&quot; and still insists upon a critique of the
limitations of increasingly (end-of-history style) hegemonic but empty
appeals to actually existing liberal democracy</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="elaboration"> [precisely when it is being
attacked in practice by the same people].</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="26" relname="preparation"> Zizek, for one, raises the
question:</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="condition"> if metanarratives don&apos;t really work</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="26" relname="span"> why do we have to explicitly
avoid them rather than taking them seriously until they self-deconstruct?</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="preparation">

The point being:</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="28" relname="span"> why treat materialists and deconstructionists as two ideal
types that help to &quot;check each other&apos;s excesses&quot; instead of thinking through
the types of &quot;obvious consequences&quot; which are alleged to follow from a
critique of representations.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> Another source might be Christopher Norris&apos;
work on What&apos;s Wrong With Postmodernism</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> or the sensitivity to the
implications of the constructivist arguments you might find about race or
gender in Paul Gilroy, David Roediger, Judith Butler, Edward Said, bell
hooks, Nancy Fraser, just to name a few.</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> (Closer to home, what about
Haraway?)</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="19" relname="circumstance">

Whether you skim _Social Text_ or read the lastest empirical history on
labor history,</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="32" relname="span"> there is a great deal of analysis of the political
consequences of constructivist positions that leads not just to
self-flagellation but to reformulating the import and relevance of those
arguments.</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="36" relname="span"> The point is they much less frequently resort to a &quot;political
veto&quot; style of argument in which there is a tacit presumption what genuinely
progressive politics entails but instead question whether &quot;obviously&quot;
progressive politics disguise a host of problematic premises?</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="20" relname="nonvolitional-result"> One does not
have to imagine oneself at the vanguard of history to try to learn from
history in this fashion.</segment>
